SIMPLE: hermaphrodite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hermaphrodite
<hw>Her*maph"ro*dite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>hermaphroditus</ets>, Gr. <?/, so called from the mythical story
that <ets>Hermaphroditus</ets>, son of Hermes and Aphrodite, when
bathing, became joined in one body with Salmacis, the nymph of a
fountain in Caria: cf. F. <ets>hermaphrodite</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>An individual which has the attributes of both
male and female, or which unites in itself the two sexes; an animal or
plant having the parts of generation of both sexes, as when a flower
contains both the stamens and pistil within the same calyx, or on the
same receptacle. In some cases reproduction may take place without the
union of the distinct individuals. In the animal kingdom true
hermaphrodites are found only among the invertebrates. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> in Appendix, under <xex>Helminths</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hermaphrodite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hermaphrodite
<hw>Her*maph"ro*dite</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Including, or being of,
both sexes; <as>as, an <ex>hermaphrodite</ex> animal or
flower</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hermaphrodite brig</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Brig</er>.</cd> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj></cs></p>

<p><ent>Hermaphroditical</ent>⟦br⟧
